&#xa0;
[normal]Further written evidence submitted by [bold]the Kyoto Club, [bold]Consorzio[bold] [bold]Italiano[bold] [bold]Compostatori[bold], [bold]Assobioplastiche[bold] and [bold]Novamont[bold] [bold]SpA[bold] [bold]1.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Contamination of the food waste recycling stream by plastic has greater negative consequences than [bold]bioplastic[bold] contamination of the plastic recycling stream.[bold]1.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]With no single-use or [bold]oxo[bold]-degradable bags made in the UK, the Government is right to prioritise minimising the environmental impact of these bags.[bold]1.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Mass communications campaigns have not been needed in Italy to deliver behaviour change, the bags themselves function as the main communication tool.[bold]1.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Correction on current standards for [bold]oxo[bold]-biodegradable bags.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Evidence submitted by WRAP – which stated 25% of household waste is food waste (7M tonnes 
[normal]tonnes
[normal]), whilst carrier bags account for 1%
[normal] (&lt;280,000 tonnes).
[normal]2.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]If it enters the household waste recycling stream, much of this plastic is sent to China to be reprocessed
[normal].
[normal]2.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Other witnesses – 
[normal]PlasRecycle
[normal] and British Polythene Industries
[normal] – currently have the capacity to process over 160,000 tonnes of waste plastic film in the UK (this includes sources of plastic film beyond 
[normal]2.4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]PlasRecycle
[normal] also stated it was possible to use IR technology to separate starch based films from polyethylene but it is not possible to separate 
[normal]oxo-degradables
[normal] from polyethylene
[normal]2.5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]According to DEFRA, the level of food waste collected and recycled by local councils from households was expected to be 300,000 tonnes
[normal] in 2013. 
[normal]2.6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]This volume of food waste can easily be contaminated by plastic bags – in Italy where overall organic recycling is at a similar level to England this result in an extra 64,000 tonnes of waste going to landfill
[normal].
[normal]2.7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] This results in significant extra costs for councils, and 
[normal]t
[normal]here is a significant opportunity to reduce this volume of food going to landfill and the quality of food waste which is then recycled. Compostable bags (already used in food bin caddy liners) have been shown to support both goals – in the UK and Italy. A trial run with the Co-op Supermarket chain in Oldham has shown that organic contamination by traditional plastics dropped by 95% in the area where local retailers promoted compostable carrier bags.
[normal] 
[normal]2.8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It has also saved the council £2000 in the first three weeks of the trial.
[normal]2.9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Unfortunately, 
[normal]oxo
[normal]-degradable bags are unsuitable for this purpose as they also contaminate organic recycling. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] More than 98% of single use plastic bags are imported 
[normal]form
[normal] the Far East
[normal].
[normal]3.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Similarly, no 
[normal]oxo
[normal]-degradable bags are produced in the UK, instead they are mainly manufactured in the Far East along with most other plastic bags through a licensing system for third party production
[normal]. On this basis, it is unlikely that an exemption for 
[normal]oxo
[normal]-biodegradable bags will lead to job creation in the UK.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal] [bold]In Italy, retailers, industry, local authorities and NGOs promote the reuse of compostable bags for food waste collection. The primary mechanism is an agreed wording, printing in a large font on all bags advising of the bags dual-use.
[normal]4.2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, the process of legislating and citizens adapting to the new system has been shown to raise awareness of environmental issues more generally.
[normal]4.3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]According to the OECD “the law has helped to build widespread citizen awareness of the need to protect the natural environment and the fundamental role played by innovation in this respect. Estimates show that 88% of Italian citizens recognise that biodegradable and compostable plastics are a key innovation capable of triggering multiple positive effects”
[normal]. 
